window.RECORDED_PAIRS = {"BRAF__MAP2K1": {"A": "BRAF", "B": "MAP2K1", "overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "comparison_summary": {"overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "strictly_better_axes_for_A": ["right_target", "right_tissue", "right_patient"], "strictly_better_axes_for_B": ["right_safety"], "tied_axes": ["right_commercial", "tractability"], "unresolved_axes": [], "reason": "both_sides_have_advantages"}, "axes": {"right_target": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "Both targets sit in the MAPK cascade and both derive their melanoma link primarily from somatic rather than germline genetics (GWAS is weak/mislocated for both). However, on causal-mechanistic strength BRAF is clearly stronger. BRAF is the canonical melanoma oncogenic driver: intoGen somatic-mutation evidence scores a maximal 1.0 with an extreme resourceScore (~6e-55, ~7e-52 in cutaneous melanoma), and the recurrent V600E kinase-activating mutation is the defining, high-frequency driver alteration of the disease. MAP2K1/MEK1 also has genuine somatic support (cancer_gene_census somatic_mutation, cancer_biomarkers affected-pathway) and a large evidence count (916 rows), but a substantial part of its top-tier association is clinical_precedence (score 1) \u2014 i.e., driven by approved MEK-inhibitor use largely in BRAF-mutant disease \u2014 rather than by a dominant, high-prevalence causal driver mutation of its own. MAP2K1 is mechanistically a downstream effector whose melanoma relevance is partly contingent on upstream BRAF activation, and its somatic mutations are comparatively rare. Direct, measured somatic driver evidence therefore favors A.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: intoGen somatic_mutation score=1.0, resourceScore=6.02e-55 (melanoma)/7.29e-52 (cutaneous melanoma) \u2014 maximal genetic-driver association", "A: recurrent V600E kinase-activating mutation is the canonical high-frequency melanoma driver", "B: melanoma link driven substantially by clinical_precedence (score 1, MEK-inhibitor use) plus cancer_gene_census somatic_mutation and cancer_biomarkers pathway evidence, with MAP2K1 mutations comparatively rare and mechanistically downstream of BRAF", "Both: germline GWAS support weak/mislocated (BRAF 8 intronic locus SNPs; MAP2K1 138 SNPs but nearest to LCTL/ZWILCH/RPL4, MAP2K1 ~55 kb upstream non-closest gene)"], "missing_evidence": ["Somatic mutation frequency/prevalence of MAP2K1 in melanoma cohorts to quantify driver strength vs BRAF", "Functional perturbation evidence (e.g. CRISPR dependency/DepMap essentiality) for each target in melanoma models", "Whether MAP2K1 somatic mutations act as independent drivers vs resistance/co-occurring alterations to BRAF"]}, "right_tissue": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Neither hypothesis has a melanoma/melanocyte-specific or disease-tissue expression anchor \u2014 both fail the core requirement of this axis, and both rely on the same off-target normal signal (BRAF and MAP2K1 each appear only as an NKT-cell marker in fetal kidney). The marginal, weak distinction is that BRAF (A) returns two additional cancer-cell (malignant-context) records in brain and lung tumors, providing at least some tumor-cell expression evidence, whereas MAP2K1 (B) returns a single record that is a normal (non-malignant) NKT cell only. A therefore has slightly more malignant-context tissue grounding, though in the wrong tumor lineages (brain/lung, not melanoma). This is not a strong preference \u2014 both are synthetic/indirect for the melanoma compartment.", "decisive_evidence": ["A (BRAF) CellMarker: 3 records \u2014 2 cancer-cell (Brain, Lung tumors) + 1 normal NKT (fetal kidney); at least some malignant-cell expression evidence.", "B (MAP2K1) CellMarker: 1 record \u2014 normal NKT cell (fetal kidney) only; no tumor-cell record at all.", "Both: no melanoma/melanocyte-specific expression record returned, so neither has a true disease-tissue anchor."], "missing_evidence": ["Single-cell or spatial data showing target expression/activity in melanoma malignant cells vs. surrounding stroma.", "Melanocyte/melanoma-lineage expression records (e.g., disease-tissue bulk or scRNA-seq of cutaneous/metastatic melanoma).", "Pathway-activity (phospho-MEK/ERK) evidence localizing MAPK signaling to the melanoma tumor compartment for either target."]}, "right_safety": {"relation": "B_better", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both targets are Tclin kinases with approved small-molecule inhibitors and broadly comparable on-target-off-tumour risk (both flagged as normal NKT-cell markers), so neither has a clean tissue-restriction safety advantage. The distinguishing evidence is mechanistic: Hypothesis A (BRAF/vemurafenib) carries a well-characterized, mechanism-based serious liability \u2014 paradoxical MAPK pathway activation driving secondary cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma \u2014 an on-target class effect explicitly documented in the report. Hypothesis B (MAP2K1/trametinib, a downstream MEK inhibitor) is not associated with paradoxical activation and reports only a generic 'substantial safety signal' without a named catastrophic mechanism. This tilts the therapeutic-window comparison toward B. The raw FAERS counts (A: 4046 vs B: 6718) are NOT decisive \u2014 they are unadjusted for exposure/market size and higher volume does not imply worse safety, so they are set aside. Because the tilt rests on a qualitative mechanistic asymmetry rather than exposure-normalized outcome data, confidence is low.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: documented paradoxical MAPK activation and cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma as a known BRAF-inhibitor on-target class effect \u2014 a specific, serious mechanism-based liability", "B: no analogous paradoxical-activation / secondary-malignancy mechanism reported for MEK1 inhibition; only a generic on-target/normal-tissue expression risk noted", "Both flagged as normal NKT-cell markers (comparable on-target-off-tumour baseline), so tissue selectivity does not separate them"], "missing_evidence": ["Exposure- or prescription-adjusted adverse-event rates (FAERS raw totals are not normalized to patient exposure)", "Serious/fatal fraction and specific toxicity spectrum for trametinib (e.g. cardiomyopathy, retinopathy, rash) to weigh against BRAF's secondary-malignancy risk", "Essentiality / knockout-phenotype and genetic-constraint data for BRAF vs MAP2K1 to assess intrinsic on-target tolerability", "Comparative therapeutic-window or dose-limiting-toxicity data from head-to-head or matched trials"]}, "right_patient": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both hypotheses have strong, biomarker-defined patient selection and completed Phase III melanoma trials, so they are close on this axis. The tie-breaker is biomarker\u2013target correspondence: for BRAF (A), the stratifying biomarker (V600E/K mutation) IS the target's own activating mutation, so the treatable subpopulation is defined directly by the target and enrolled patients (NCT01307397, NCT01689519) are selected on that exact molecular lesion. For MAP2K1 (B), patients are still stratified by BRAF genotype (plus LDH), i.e. the selection biomarker sits upstream of the actual target rather than on MAP2K1 itself, making the target-to-population link slightly less direct. B does offer breadth (30 trials, adjuvant COMBI-AD ~852 pts, high-unmet-need setting), which nearly offsets this, hence low confidence.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: BRAF V600E/K mutation is both the target lesion and the enrollment biomarker in completed Phase III trials (NCT01307397, NCT01689519) \u2014 direct target-matched patient selection.", "B: trametinib melanoma trials (30, incl. Phase III COMBI-AD ~852 pts) stratify by BRAF genotype and LDH, i.e. biomarker is upstream of MAP2K1 rather than on the target itself."], "missing_evidence": ["Head-to-head clinical benefit magnitude (ORR/PFS/OS) for the target-defined populations in each hypothesis.", "Whether any MAP2K1-specific (e.g. MEK1 mutation) biomarker defines a distinct treatable population beyond BRAF-mutant melanoma.", "Comparative unmet-need / population size for the specific indications enrolled in each program."]}, "right_commercial": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both hypotheses describe mature, crowded small-molecule spaces in melanoma with approved drugs and Phase III registration precedent. BRAF (vemurafenib/Zelboraf, ~27 melanoma trials) and MAP2K1/MEK1 (trametinib, 30 melanoma trials) sit in the same de-risked but heavily competed BRAF/MAPK-pathway landscape, and the two targets are in fact clinically co-developed as combination regimens (BRAF+MEK, e.g. vemurafenib+cobimetinib, dabrafenib+trametinib). Neither report identifies meaningful commercial whitespace or differentiated positioning; both explicitly flag low novelty (Tclin, novelty ~0.0025 vs ~0.0005) and crowding. MAP2K1's report adds only that no antibody therapeutics exist (expected for an intracellular kinase \u2014 not a whitespace signal). On strategic differentiation and market opportunity the two are materially similar, so no fair ordering favors one over the other.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: 27 vemurafenib melanoma trials incl. Phase 3, approved ZELBORAF (Genentech) \u2014 high validation, crowded, self-described 'limited whitespace'", "B: 30 trametinib melanoma trials incl. completed Phase III, approved MEK1/2 inhibitor 'often combined with dabrafenib' \u2014 equally mature/crowded", "Both targets act in the same BRAF/MAPK pathway and are marketed as combination therapy, indicating shared rather than distinct commercial niches", "Both graded Tclin with near-zero novelty scores, confirming well-explored, de-risked commercial positions"], "missing_evidence": ["Explicit market-size, revenue, or pricing data for either franchise", "Analysis of unmet-need or resistance segments that either target could uniquely address (whitespace)", "Competitive-intensity comparison (number of distinct sponsors/assets, not just trial counts)", "Any differentiation in indication niche beyond overlapping BRAF V600-mutant metastatic melanoma"]}, "tractability": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "Both targets are at the ceiling of tractability on every dimension this axis cares about. Both are Pharos Tclin (target of an approved drug) in the Kinase family, both have direct small-molecule modality precedent with an FDA-approved inhibitor in the exact disease context (BRAF: vemurafenib/Zelboraf; MAP2K1/MEK1: trametinib), both have well-characterized ATP-binding pockets, established assays, and mature developability with combination-regimen precedent (BRAF+MEK). Neither hypothesis presents a modality-fit gap: both are intracellular kinases best drugged by small molecules, and TheraSAbDab correctly shows 0 antibodies for MAP2K1 (expected, not a deficit). The differences that exist (novelty score 0.0025 vs 0.0005; publication count 2635 vs 399) reflect degree of prior exploration, not feasibility of modulation, and do not create a fair ordering on tractability. Both are maximally tractable.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: Pharos tdl=Tclin, Kinase family, approved inhibitor vemurafenib (P15056)", "B: Pharos tdl=Tclin, Kinase family, approved inhibitor trametinib (Q02750)", "Both have completed Phase III small-molecule trials in melanoma (BRAF V600 vemurafenib; trametinib COMBI regimens)", "Both are intracellular kinases with correct small-molecule modality fit; TheraSAbDab 0 antibodies for MAP2K1 is expected, not a liability"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct structural/ligand-quality metrics (co-crystal pocket druggability scores, ligand efficiency) for a head-to-head pocket comparison", "Explicit developability/delivery data distinguishing the two approved chemotypes"]}}}, "BRAF__TERT": {"A": "BRAF", "B": "TERT", "overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "comparison_summary": {"overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "strictly_better_axes_for_A": ["right_target", "right_patient", "right_commercial", "tractability"], "strictly_better_axes_for_B": [], "tied_axes": ["right_tissue"], "unresolved_axes": ["right_safety"], "reason": "insufficient_evidence"}, "axes": {"right_target": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both targets are genuine, causally-supported melanoma drivers with somatic-mutation evidence, so this is a comparison between two strong hypotheses rather than strong-vs-weak. BRAF's top-tier support is a directly measured somatic-driver signal: intoGen somatic_mutation score=1.0 with an extreme resourceScore (~6e-55 melanoma / ~7e-52 cutaneous), and the recurrent V600E kinase-activating mutation is the canonical, mechanistically-characterized oncogenic driver with clear pathway causality (constitutive MAPK activation). TERT is also causally grounded \u2014 its 5p15.33 GWAS locus and cancer_gene_census somatic record correspond to the well-known recurrent TERT promoter mutations \u2014 but the report's maximal-score TERT evidence is europepmc literature association (resourceScore up to ~204), which is closer to curated-literature/co-mention support than the direct driver-detection statistics behind BRAF. Weighing curated/measured somatic-driver evidence over literature-weighted association, BRAF edges ahead on the strength and directness of causal/mechanistic support, though TERT is not far behind.", "decisive_evidence": ["BRAF: intoGen somatic_mutation score=1.0, resourceScore ~6.02e-55 (melanoma) / 7.29e-52 (cutaneous) \u2014 direct somatic-driver detection with extreme statistical significance", "BRAF: recurrent V600E kinase-activating mutation is the canonical, mechanistically-defined melanoma oncogenic driver with explicit MAPK pathway causality", "TERT: strongest evidence is europepmc literature associations (score=1.0 but resourceScore up to ~204), with cancer_gene_census somatic record and 50 SNPs confined to the 5p15.33 promoter locus \u2014 genuine but more literature/association-weighted"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct perturbation/functional evidence (e.g. CRISPR dependency or knockdown) quantifying melanoma-cell reliance on each target", "A driver-detection somatic score for TERT promoter mutations comparable to BRAF's intoGen metric (to fairly weight TERT beyond literature association)", "Human germline/heritability causal estimates distinguishing the somatic vs inherited contribution for each target"]}, "right_tissue": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both hypotheses rely on the same datasource (CellMarker) and neither returns any melanoma-, skin-, or melanocyte-specific tissue record. BRAF has 3 human records (2 cancer-cell: Brain, Lung; 1 normal fetal-kidney NKT cell), and TERT has 4 human records (2 cancer-cell: Brain, Lung; 2 normal embryonic stem cell). In both cases the target's expression is demonstrably not tumour-restricted and, critically, is not documented in the melanoma compartment. Both show pan-cancer expression patterns plus normal-tissue expression (fetal kidney NKT for BRAF; embryonic stem cells for TERT). Neither provides single-cell, spatial, or disease-tissue evidence localizing the target to malignant melanoma tissue, so tissue-context disease relevance is only indirectly inferred for both. The self-graded difference (BRAF 'weak' vs TERT 'moderate') is not substantiated by any melanoma-tissue evidence favoring either, so they are materially similar on this axis.", "decisive_evidence": ["Neither target has a melanoma/skin/melanocyte CellMarker record \u2014 both localize only to Brain and Lung cancer cells plus normal non-melanoma compartments.", "BRAF normal expression in fetal-kidney NKT cells; TERT normal expression in embryonic stem cells \u2014 both indicate non-tumour-restricted, non-melanoma-tissue expression.", "Both rely solely on CellMarker curated records with no single-cell or spatial disease-tissue data."], "missing_evidence": ["Single-cell or spatial transcriptomics of melanoma tumours showing target expression in malignant melanocytes vs. stroma for either target.", "Melanoma-tissue or melanocyte-specific expression/activity records to establish disease-compartment localization.", "Disease-state-specific (malignant vs. normal melanocyte) evidence to differentiate the two targets on tissue context."]}, "right_safety": {"relation": "insufficient_evidence", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "The two hypotheses rest on non-comparable evidence bases. BRAF (A) has direct, real-world safety data: a marketed inhibitor (vemurafenib) with 4046 openFDA adverse-event reports, a high serious/fatal fraction, and well-characterized on-target class liabilities (paradoxical MAPK activation, cutaneous squamous-cell carcinoma). Critically, however, that same clinical experience demonstrates a usable therapeutic window \u2014 the target is approved and its toxicities are managed in practice. TERT (B) has NO direct safety data at all: no approved drug, so no post-market AE profile could be queried. Its only safety signal is indirect \u2014 CellMarker expression in normal embryonic/embryonic-stem cells, flagging a plausible on-target liability in the physiological telomerase-active (stem/germline-like) compartment, which if real would imply a narrow window. But this is an expression-based inference, not a measured toxicity or knockout-phenotype readout. We therefore cannot fairly order them: A's evidence is direct AEs but from a target with a demonstrated clinical window, while B's evidence is a theoretical essentiality concern with no clinical confirmation. Preferring direct/grounded evidence, A's profile is far better characterized, but 'more data showing real toxicity' does not straightforwardly beat 'no data plus a stem-cell red flag,' so a confident directional call is unsupported.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: vemurafenib openFDA 4046 AE reports with high serious/fatal fraction and known paradoxical-MAPK / cutaneous-SCC class effects (direct human safety data)", "A: target is clinically approved (Tclin), implying a demonstrated, manageable therapeutic window despite documented toxicities", "B: no marketed TERT drug \u2014 OpenFDA not queryable, so zero direct clinical safety evidence", "B: CellMarker TERT expression in normal embryonic/embryonic-stem cells, an indirect on-target liability in the physiological telomerase-active compartment"], "missing_evidence": ["For TERT: any clinical or preclinical toxicity data (AEs, tolerated dose, therapeutic window) for a telomerase-directed agent", "Knockout/essentiality phenotypes and genetic-constraint (e.g. LoF intolerance) metrics for both targets to gauge on-target-off-tumour risk", "Direct tissue-distribution comparison in adult normal tissues, especially proliferative/germline compartments for TERT", "Severity-normalized comparison of BRAF-inhibitor toxicities against any measured TERT-inhibition tolerability, rather than expression inference"]}, "right_patient": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "On the right_patient axis, Hypothesis A (BRAF) is clearly stronger. BRAF offers a validated molecular stratification biomarker (V600E/K mutation status) that defines a treatable subpopulation, with completed Phase 3 trials (NCT01307397, NCT01689519) that enrolled BRAF V600-mutation-positive metastatic melanoma patients and an FDA-approved therapy (vemurafenib) demonstrating real, measured patient benefit and clinical precedent. Hypothesis B (TERT) has strong target genetics but zero melanoma clinical trials for any TERT/telomerase intervention ('No studies found'), no approved or clinical-stage drug, and thus no demonstrated patient population, endpoints, or therapeutic benefit in the clinic. While TERT addresses potential unmet need, right_patient rewards defined populations, biomarkers, clinical precedent, and plausible demonstrated benefit \u2014 all directly evidenced for BRAF and absent for TERT.", "decisive_evidence": ["BRAF: V600E/K mutation is an established patient-selection biomarker; completed Phase 3 trials enrolled V600+ metastatic melanoma patients (NCT01307397, NCT01689519), with approved vemurafenib.", "TERT: search_clinical_trials returned 'No studies found' for both TERT and telomerase interventions in melanoma; no clinical-stage or approved drug (grade 'absent')."], "missing_evidence": ["For TERT: any early-phase clinical activity, defined biomarker-selected melanoma subpopulation, or evidence that promoter-mutation status could serve as a patient-selection axis.", "For BRAF: magnitude/durability of clinical benefit and unmet-need context relative to newer standards (immunotherapy), though this does not change the direction on this axis."]}, "right_commercial": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "BRAF-in-melanoma is a fully validated, monetizable commercial space: an FDA-approved product (Zelboraf/Genentech) plus MEK-combination regimens and 27 registered vemurafenib melanoma trials including multiple Phase 3s. This is a crowded, de-risked market with limited whitespace, but it is a proven, revenue-generating indication with a clear competitive structure and demonstrated willingness to invest. TERT, by contrast, shows count=0 antibody therapeutics (Thera-SAbDab), no melanoma clinical assets, and is described as not antibody-tractable \u2014 its 'whitespace' is empty not because of an attractive uncontested niche but because the target has no established path to market (intracellular reverse transcriptase, no approved therapeutic, no clinical pipeline). On strict commercial attractiveness \u2014 market opportunity plus a viable competitive position \u2014 A's proven, differentiable-within-combinations market outweighs B's undeveloped, low-tractability void. The comparison is close because B does offer genuine strategic whitespace/novelty, which is why confidence is medium rather than high.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: approved product ZELBORAF (Genentech, NDA202429) + MEK-combo regimens, 27 registered melanoma trials incl. multiple Phase 3 \u2014 validated, monetizable market.", "B: TheraSAbDab count=0 (no antibody therapeutics), no melanoma clinical-trial assets, characterized as not antibody-tractable \u2014 no competitive pipeline and no clear commercialization path."], "missing_evidence": ["Market-size / revenue and pricing data for the melanoma indication to quantify opportunity for each target.", "Small-molecule (non-antibody) competitive pipeline for TERT, since Thera-SAbDab only covers antibody modalities and may understate TERT's real competitive/whitespace picture.", "Assessment of remaining differentiation/whitespace within the crowded BRAF space (e.g., resistance-overcoming or next-generation assets)."]}, "tractability": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "On tractability, BRAF (A) is clearly superior. Pharos classifies BRAF as Tclin \u2014 the highest druggability tier \u2014 meaning it is already a clinically drugged target with an FDA-approved small-molecule inhibitor (vemurafenib/Zelboraf) and combination regimens (MEK inhibitors), plus a structurally well-defined kinase ATP pocket and validated V600E-selective assayability. This is maximal modality-target fit with direct clinical precedent. TERT (B) is only Tchem: small-molecule ligands with activity data exist, but there is no approved therapeutic, no clinical asset, and no antibody tractability (Thera-SAbDab count=0). As an intracellular reverse transcriptase, TERT is a harder modality-target proposition with no demonstrated clinical modulation. Direct approved-drug precedent for BRAF decisively outranks TERT's ligand-only status.", "decisive_evidence": ["BRAF Pharos tdl=Tclin (clinically drugged), Kinase family, approved inhibitor vemurafenib (NDA202429)", "TERT Pharos tdl=Tchem \u2014 chemical matter but no clinical drug, Enzyme (reverse transcriptase)", "TERT has no antibody therapeutics (Thera-SAbDab count=0) and no clinical assets; intracellular target with harder modality fit", "BRAF has structural kinase pocket + V600-selective assayability and MEK-combo developability"], "missing_evidence": ["Quantitative ligand-quality/potency metrics for TERT chemical matter (e.g. best-in-class Ki/IC50, ligand efficiency)", "Assessment of TERT small-molecule developability/delivery feasibility for a catalytic reverse-transcriptase pocket", "Structural pocket/co-crystal data comparison for TERT versus BRAF"]}}}, "KDR__ATM": {"A": "KDR", "B": "ATM", "overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "comparison_summary": {"overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "strictly_better_axes_for_A": ["right_patient", "tractability"], "strictly_better_axes_for_B": [], "tied_axes": ["right_target", "right_tissue", "right_safety"], "unresolved_axes": ["right_commercial"], "reason": "incomparable_axes"}, "axes": {"right_target": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both targets rest on the same evidence architecture and both are graded 'moderate' with no melanoma-selective causal signal. KDR has more curated volume \u2014 541 OpenTargets rows vs 270, and Cancer Gene Census somatic-mutation evidence spanning three melanoma subtypes (desmoplastic, nodular, superficial-spreading) vs two for ATM \u2014 which is a modest breadth advantage. But the axis rewards causal/mechanistic disease relevance, not row count, and here the two roughly offset: KDR's association is largely vascular/angiogenic (a normal endothelial marker, stromal rather than tumor-cell-intrinsic), weakening its claim as a melanoma driver, whereas ATM is a canonical DNA-damage-response tumor suppressor whose somatic loss is a mechanistically clean but broad, non-melanoma-selective driver. Neither shows a germline GWAS trait association \u2014 both return only unannotated intron/intergenic SNPs at their loci \u2014 so neither demonstrates a causal human-genetics link to melanoma. KDR's extra curated somatic breadth is counterbalanced by ATM's more direct tumor-suppressor mechanism, leaving them materially similar on this axis.", "decisive_evidence": ["Both carry Cancer Gene Census somatic_mutation evidence tying the target to specific melanoma subtypes (KDR: desmoplastic/nodular/superficial-spreading; ATM: nodular/superficial-spreading)", "Neither has a melanoma trait-annotated germline GWAS association \u2014 both return only generic intron/intergenic SNPs (KDR 50 at 4q12, ATM 12 at 11q22.3) with no phenotype fields", "KDR's greater evidence volume (541 vs 270 rows) is offset by its angiogenic/endothelial rather than tumor-intrinsic mechanism; ATM offers a cleaner DDR tumor-suppressor causal story but is broad, not melanoma-selective"], "missing_evidence": ["Perturbation/functional evidence (CRISPR dependency, DepMap essentiality) in melanoma cell lines for either target", "Trait-annotated germline association or fine-mapped causal variant linking either locus to melanoma risk", "Pathway-causality evidence distinguishing tumor-cell-intrinsic driver role from stromal/microenvironment involvement (especially for KDR)"]}, "right_tissue": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Neither hypothesis presents melanoma-tissue-selective or melanocyte-restricted expression evidence; both fail the disease-context test on this axis. KDR (A) has 64 CellMarker human records but they are overwhelmingly normal vascular/endothelial across many tissues, with only a handful of non-melanoma cancer records (tumor endothelial cells, bone cancer stem cell) \u2014 expression is broad and vascular, not tumor-cell-intrinsic to melanoma. ATM (B) has 6 CellMarker records in normal immune/CNS contexts plus one non-melanoma gastric cancer T cell \u2014 expression is ubiquitous (consistent with a housekeeping DNA-damage-response gene), also with no melanoma or melanocyte record. Both are curated CellMarker data (not purely synthetic), and both lack any single-cell, spatial, or disease-tissue evidence establishing the target in the right melanoma cell/context. KDR has marginally more cancer-adjacent tissue records, but they are tumor-endothelial/stromal rather than malignant melanoma cells, so this does not confer a defensible disease-context edge. The two are materially similar: both weak, both non-selective for melanoma tissue.", "decisive_evidence": ["A/KDR: 64 human CellMarker records dominated by normal endothelial/vascular cells (heart, kidney, lung, liver, eye); no melanoma or melanocyte record.", "B/ATM: 6 human CellMarker records in normal immune/CNS cell types plus one non-melanoma gastric cancer T cell; no melanocyte or melanoma-tissue record.", "Neither report includes single-cell, spatial, or malignant-vs-stromal evidence localizing the target to melanoma tissue/cells."], "missing_evidence": ["Single-cell or spatial transcriptomics showing target expression in malignant melanoma cells vs. stroma/normal tissue.", "Melanocyte-lineage or melanoma-disease-state expression data for both targets.", "Protein-level (IHC) tumor-cell-intrinsic expression in melanoma patient samples."]}, "right_safety": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both targets carry serious on-target safety liabilities driven by broad normal-tissue expression, and neither is clearly safer. KDR (VEGFR2) has direct, grounded evidence of serious multi-organ toxicity: 15,246 lenvatinib adverse-event cases with life-threatening cardiac failure, toxic nephropathy, and hypertension, consistent with KDR being a normal endothelial marker in heart, kidney, and lung \u2014 a well-characterized on-target vascular/renal window problem. ATM has a strong essentiality liability (germline biallelic loss causes ataxia telangiectasia, and it is broadly expressed across immune and CNS cells), but its safety profile is inferred, not measured: no ATM-directed drug exists, so no adverse-event data is available, and germline recessive loss is not equivalent to transient pharmacologic inhibition. KDR's liability is severe but documented and clinically managed; ATM's is systemic in principle but unquantified. These offset to a materially similar, weak-evidence standing rather than a clear ordering.", "decisive_evidence": ["KDR: 15,246 lenvatinib adverse-event reports with serious cardiac failure, toxic nephropathy, and hypertension \u2014 direct on-target VEGFR2 vascular/renal toxicity", "KDR expressed as normal endothelial marker in heart, kidney, and lung (CellMarker), mechanistically explaining the observed class toxicity", "ATM germline biallelic loss causes ataxia telangiectasia and ATM is broadly expressed in immune/CNS cells, indicating systemic essentiality", "ATM has no approved/clinical drug, so no direct pharmacologic safety data exists (OpenFDA not applicable)"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct clinical tolerability/adverse-event data for pharmacologic ATM inhibition (vs. germline loss)", "Comparative therapeutic-window or MTD data quantifying on-target margin for each target", "Knockout/conditional phenotype data distinguishing acute inhibition toxicity from developmental essentiality for ATM", "Melanoma-tissue-selective expression data to assess off-tumor exposure for either target"]}, "right_patient": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "On patient impact and clinical relevance, KDR (A) is clearly stronger. A has a substantial, clinically advanced melanoma patient program: 9 melanoma trials of the VEGFR2/KDR inhibitor lenvatinib, including two completed Phase 3 studies of lenvatinib + pembrolizumab in first-line advanced melanoma (LEAP-003, NCT03820986) and Phase 2 studies in defined populations such as uveal melanoma (NCT05308901) and anti-PD-1-exposed melanoma (LEAP-004). This demonstrates defined patient populations, meaningful late-phase clinical endpoints, and real therapeutic testing in melanoma. B (ATM) has no ATM-directed intervention in melanoma at all; the single retrieved trial (NCT03207347) tests niraparib, a PARP inhibitor, with ATM serving only as a DDR-pathway stratification biomarker, not the drug target. B thus offers no ATM-drug-in-clinic and no demonstrated patient benefit for the hypothesized target, only biomarker-level relevance in a broader DDR-deficient population.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: 9 melanoma trials of KDR inhibitor lenvatinib incl. 2 completed Phase 3 (LEAP-003 NCT03820986) \u2014 advanced clinical program with defined populations and endpoints (grade: strong)", "A: Phase 2 programs in specific populations \u2014 uveal melanoma (NCT05308901) and anti-PD-1-exposed melanoma (LEAP-004 NCT03776136)", "B: No ATM-directed intervention in melanoma; only NCT03207347 (niraparib/PARP) where ATM is a stratification biomarker, not the drug target (grade: absent)"], "missing_evidence": ["Reported clinical outcomes/efficacy (ORR, PFS, OS) for lenvatinib melanoma trials to confirm actual patient benefit vs. mere program existence", "Any early-phase or planned trial of a direct ATM inhibitor (e.g., in DDR-deficient or ATM-mutant melanoma) that would give B some patient footing", "Unmet-need and biomarker-enrichment data for the specific KDR melanoma populations vs. ATM-defined DDR-deficient subgroups"]}, "right_commercial": {"relation": "incomparable", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "The two hypotheses embody the opposite poles of this axis, which bundles two properties that conflict here: 'commercial attractiveness' (validated, monetizable market) versus 'strategic whitespace' (uncrowded differentiation). KDR is a commercially validated but crowded target \u2014 TheraSAbDab lists 6 antibody therapeutics (ramucirumab Approved; pulocimab Phase 3; olinvacimab Phase 2), plus an advanced melanoma small-molecule program (lenvatinib, two completed Phase 3 LEAP studies). That is a proven, attractive market but a poor competitive position with little differentiation. ATM is pure whitespace \u2014 0 antibody therapeutics and no ATM-directed clinical asset in melanoma (only an adjacent PARP-inhibitor trial) \u2014 offering maximal differentiation and no competitors, but also no validated commercial path or demonstrated market pull, and no directly marketable ATM melanoma product. Ordering 'crowded-but-proven' against 'open-but-unproven' requires a strategic weighting (fast-follower vs first-mover) that this axis does not fix, so neither can be fairly ranked above the other on the evidence given.", "decisive_evidence": ["KDR: 6 KDR/VEGFR2 antibody therapeutics incl. 1 Approved (ramucirumab), 1 Phase 3, 1 Phase 2, plus lenvatinib melanoma Phase 3 program \u2014 validated but crowded, weak differentiation.", "ATM: TheraSAbDab count=0 therapeutics and no ATM-directed melanoma trial (only niraparib/PARP) \u2014 clear whitespace but no validated commercial path or product."], "missing_evidence": ["Market size / commercial forecast for a melanoma DDR/ATM-targeted asset to judge whether ATM whitespace reflects opportunity or lack of viability.", "Strategic weighting between first-mover whitespace and validated-market fast-follower positioning, which the axis leaves unspecified.", "Competitive-intensity or pricing/differentiation data for the crowded KDR melanoma space to assess residual commercial headroom."]}, "tractability": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "KDR (A) is Pharos Tclin \u2014 the highest development level, meaning approved drugs already modulate it. It has a directly relevant, clinically advanced modality precedent (small-molecule VEGFR2 inhibitor lenvatinib in two completed Phase 3 melanoma trials) plus an approved antibody (ramucirumab) and multiple active antibody programs against the same target. ATM (B) is only Pharos Tchem \u2014 it has chemical probes/tool-compound ligands but no approved drug, no antibody therapeutic (Thera-SAbDab count=0), and no direct ATM-targeted intervention in melanoma (the sole related trial targets PARP, not ATM). Both are well-studied kinases with established chemotypes, so ATM is druggable in principle, but on the axis definition (direct modality precedent, approved drugs, clinical assets, modality-target fit) A is clearly ahead: clinically validated and drugged versus probe-stage with no approved modulator.", "decisive_evidence": ["KDR: Pharos Tclin (existing approved drugs) vs ATM: Pharos Tchem (chemical probes only, no approved drug)", "KDR has approved therapeutics \u2014 small molecule lenvatinib (VEGFR2/KDR) in two completed Phase 3 melanoma trials and approved mAb ramucirumab; ATM has zero approved drugs and zero antibody therapeutics (Thera-SAbDab=0)", "No direct ATM-targeted intervention exists in melanoma; the closest asset targets PARP (niraparib), not ATM itself"], "missing_evidence": ["Structural/pocket and ligand-quality (e.g., co-crystal, probe potency/selectivity) details for ATM to gauge intrinsic druggability beyond development-level tier", "Whether existing ATM inhibitor chemotypes are advancing toward the clinic in any indication (development momentum outside melanoma)"]}}}, "MAP2K1__CDK4": {"A": "MAP2K1", "B": "CDK4", "overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "comparison_summary": {"overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "strictly_better_axes_for_A": ["right_patient", "right_commercial", "tractability"], "strictly_better_axes_for_B": ["right_target"], "tied_axes": ["right_tissue", "right_safety"], "unresolved_axes": [], "reason": "both_sides_have_advantages"}, "axes": {"right_target": {"relation": "B_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both targets have genuine somatic-mutation causal evidence in melanoma (Cancer Gene Census for MAP2K1 and CDK4) and both have weak germline GWAS support. The distinguishing factor on this axis, which prioritizes causal human/somatic genetics and curated disease-biology causality over clinical precedent or literature popularity, is that CDK4 (B) carries a curated score=1.0 gene2phenotype genetic-literature association with cutaneous melanoma plus Genomics England panel support \u2014 reflecting CDK4's established germline/familial melanoma-predisposition role (CDKN2A/CDK4 axis). This is direct human-genetics causal grounding for target-disease relevance. MAP2K1's (A) strongest OpenTargets signal is clinical_precedence (score 1), which encodes drug-approval precedence rather than causal disease biology and should not be over-weighted on this axis; its causal disease link rests mainly on somatic mutation and pathway-biomarker evidence. With clinical-precedence discounted, CDK4's combination of curated germline genetic association plus somatic evidence provides marginally stronger causal/mechanistic support for target-disease relevance. The larger raw OpenTargets row count for CDK4 (2136 vs 916) is not itself decisive (popularity), but the presence of a distinct gene2phenotype germline pillar is.", "decisive_evidence": ["B: score=1.0 gene2phenotype genetic-literature association with cutaneous melanoma (germline/familial CDK4 predisposition; PMIDs 7652577, 9425228) plus Genomics England support", "B: Cancer Gene Census somatic-mutation entry (nodular malignant melanoma, PMID 36219477)", "A: Cancer Gene Census somatic_mutation + cancer_biomarkers affected-pathway evidence (real causal support), but its top-scoring pillar is clinical_precedence (drug precedence, down-weighted on this axis)", "Both: germline GWAS support weak (A: 138 SNPs but intronic/intergenic to neighbor genes; B: only 3 SNPs, no melanoma trait)"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct perturbation/functional evidence (CRISPR dependency, DepMap) linking either target causally to melanoma proliferation", "Effect sizes / odds ratios for the germline CDK4 melanoma association to gauge causal strength", "Quantitative comparison of somatic mutation frequency and driver status for MAP2K1 vs CDK4 in melanoma cohorts"]}, "right_tissue": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "Both hypotheses have essentially no positive melanoma-tissue localization. For MAP2K1 (A), CellMarker returns a single Human record \u2014 an NKT-cell marker in fetal kidney (normal tissue), with zero melanoma/melanocyte/skin records. For CDK4 (B), CellMarker returns 2 Human records, both in fetal gonad (mitotic germ cell, Leydig cell), also with zero melanocyte/skin records. In both cases the only cell-type evidence is off-target normal tissue unrelated to cutaneous melanoma, and neither anchors the target's presence, activity, or disease-relevance in the correct tumor tissue or malignant cell context. No single-cell, spatial, disease-tissue, or malignant-vs-stromal evidence is provided for either. The trivial difference (1 vs 2 irrelevant records, both fetal/normal) does not support ordering one above the other on this axis.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: CellMarker_search_by_gene total_records=1 \u2014 NKT cell, fetal kidney, normal cell; 0 melanoma/melanocyte records", "B: CellMarker_search_by_gene = 2 Human records \u2014 fetal gonad germ/Leydig cells; 0 melanocyte/skin records", "Neither report supplies single-cell, spatial, or disease-tissue (malignant melanoma) expression evidence for the target"], "missing_evidence": ["Single-cell or spatial expression of MAP2K1/CDK4 in melanoma tumor tissue (malignant vs stromal cells)", "Melanocyte-lineage or skin-tissue expression/activity data for either target", "Disease-state-specific (cutaneous/metastatic melanoma) protein or phospho-activity localization"]}, "right_safety": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both targets present materially similar safety profiles on this axis. Each is a broadly-expressed, essential kinase (MAP2K1/MEK1 in the MAPK cascade; CDK4 as a core G1-S cell-cycle kinase), implying comparable on-target toxicity risk in normal proliferating/physiological tissue, and CellMarker places both in normal-cell contexts (NKT for MAP2K1, fetal gonad germ/Leydig for CDK4). Both are approved-drug (Tclin) modalities with substantial real-world FAERS burden and documented serious events. The raw FAERS counts (trametinib 6,718 vs palbociclib 11,048) are not a valid safety-margin comparator because they are confounded by market exposure, indication breadth, and reporting volume rather than intrinsic therapeutic window; neither report provides an exposure-normalized rate, a knockout-phenotype/essentiality metric, or a genetic-constraint measure that would order the two. Absent such normalized evidence, the two are similar and cannot be fairly separated on safety.", "decisive_evidence": ["Both flagged as broadly/normally expressed essential kinases with implied on-target toxicity in normal tissue (CellMarker normal-cell records for both; MEK cascade vs cell-cycle kinase)", "Both are approved modalities with substantial serious-event FAERS burden (trametinib 6,718; palbociclib 11,048 with sampled acute pancreatitis)", "FAERS totals differ but are exposure-confounded, not a normalized therapeutic-window measure"], "missing_evidence": ["Exposure-normalized adverse-event rates (per-patient or per-exposure) rather than raw report counts", "Genetic constraint / essentiality metrics (e.g. pLI, DepMap dependency) for MAP2K1 vs CDK4", "Knockout phenotype severity and tissue-distribution/therapeutic-window data for each target"]}, "right_patient": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "On patient impact and clinical relevance, Hypothesis A (MAP2K1/trametinib) is clearly stronger. A has 30 melanoma trials with multiple completed Phase III studies (e.g., COMBI-AD adjuvant ~852 pts, NCT01584648, NCT01245062 vs chemotherapy ~297 pts) and well-established biomarker-defined patient stratification (BRAF V600E/K genotype, LDH), reflecting an approved therapy addressing a defined high-unmet-need melanoma population with meaningful clinical endpoints. Hypothesis B (CDK4/palbociclib) has only 4 melanoma studies, maxing out at Phase 2, with the two dedicated BRAF-melanoma combination trials TERMINATED and no melanoma-specific approval \u2014 indicating an unproven, below-threshold patient path in this disease. Both are Tclin kinases, but melanoma-specific clinical precedent and biomarker-defined patient selection strongly favor A.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: 30 trametinib melanoma trials, multiple completed Phase III with BRAF-genotype/LDH biomarker stratification; approved MEK inhibitor in melanoma", "B: only 4 melanoma studies, max PHASE2, 2 of 4 TERMINATED, no melanoma-specific approval or pivotal program"], "missing_evidence": ["Response/survival endpoint magnitudes and unmet-need quantification for each melanoma subpopulation", "Reasons for termination of the CDK4 melanoma combination trials (safety vs. efficacy vs. strategic)"]}, "right_commercial": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "high", "rationale": "On commercial attractiveness in melanoma, A (MAP2K1/MEK) has direct, established validation: 30 melanoma trials including completed Phase III registration studies for trametinib, an approved MEK1/2 inhibitor marketed for melanoma (often with dabrafenib). This is a proven, reimbursed melanoma market position with clear biomarker-defined commercial footing. B (CDK4) has approved CDK4/6 small-molecule precedent (palbociclib/IBRANCE) but only in breast cancer, not melanoma; its melanoma-specific footprint is limited to 4 early-phase trials with the two dedicated BRAF-melanoma combination programs TERMINATED and no melanoma approval. While B could be framed as commercial whitespace in melanoma, the terminated dedicated programs signal a failed/unproven opportunity rather than attractive, capturable whitespace, and there is no melanoma-specific commercial validation. A therefore has a materially stronger competitive position and clearer, de-risked market opportunity in the target indication.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: trametinib is an approved MEK1/2 inhibitor for melanoma with completed Phase III registration studies (search_clinical_trials, 30 trials)", "B: CDK4/6 inhibitor palbociclib approved only in breast cancer, not melanoma (TheraSAbDab/search_clinical_trials; palbociclib NDA breast cancer)", "B: melanoma-specific footprint limited to 4 early-phase trials with 2 of 4 dedicated BRAF-melanoma programs TERMINATED and no melanoma approval"], "missing_evidence": ["Market-size, pricing, or revenue data for the melanoma indication for either target", "Competitive landscape / crowding metrics (number of active competitor programs) specific to melanoma", "Strategic differentiation analysis for a novel CDK4 melanoma entry vs. the crowded, mature MEK-inhibitor melanoma market (potential whitespace argument for B)"]}, "tractability": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both targets are highly tractable small-molecule kinases: each is Pharos Tclin (target of an approved drug), Kinase family, with low novelty and hundreds of publications, and both correctly show 0 antibody therapeutics (intracellular targets whose modality is small-molecule). On pure druggability they are close to a tie. MAP2K1 gains a clear tractability edge because its modality precedent is direct for the disease context: trametinib is an approved MEK1/2 small-molecule inhibitor with completed Phase III melanoma registration programs and established biomarker-based patient selection, demonstrating a proven, developable, delivery-feasible molecule against this exact target in melanoma. CDK4's approved-drug precedent (palbociclib) is validated only in breast cancer; its melanoma-directed programs are limited to early-phase trials with the two dedicated BRAF-melanoma combinations terminated, so the modality-target fit is proven for CDK4/6 in general but not demonstrated as a mature, developable path in the melanoma setting. Given tractability rewards direct modality precedent and developable, delivery-feasible molecules, A's approved in-disease small-molecule precedent outweighs B's out-of-indication approval and terminated melanoma programs.", "decisive_evidence": ["MAP2K1: approved MEK1/2 inhibitor trametinib with completed Phase III melanoma registration trials (direct modality precedent in the disease)", "CDK4: approved inhibitor (palbociclib) is validated in breast cancer only; melanoma programs limited to early-phase, with two dedicated BRAF-melanoma trials TERMINATED", "Both are Pharos Tclin, Kinase-family, intracellular small-molecule targets with 0 therapeutic antibodies (comparable core druggability)"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct ligand-quality / structural-pocket metrics (e.g., co-crystal structures, ChEMBL potent-ligand counts) for both targets to compare intrinsic druggability beyond the Tclin label", "Assayability and selectivity data (MEK1 vs. CDK4/6 kinase selectivity windows)", "Whether CDK4-specific (vs. CDK4/6 dual) modulation is achievable, which affects modality-target fit"]}}}, "MTOR__ERBB2": {"A": "MTOR", "B": "ERBB2", "overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "comparison_summary": {"overall_relation": "tradeoff_or_unresolved", "strictly_better_axes_for_A": ["right_target", "right_patient"], "strictly_better_axes_for_B": ["right_commercial", "tractability"], "tied_axes": ["right_tissue", "right_safety"], "unresolved_axes": [], "reason": "both_sides_have_advantages"}, "axes": {"right_target": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Both targets draw their disease-association signal primarily from the Cancer Gene Census somatic_mutation datasource (score 1.0) rather than melanoma-specific human genetics, and neither has melanoma-trait GWAS hits. However, MTOR (A) is flagged as a somatic-mutation driver across multiple melanoma subtypes (cutaneous, superficial-spreading, nodular, desmoplastic) with substantially more evidence rows (1172 vs 764) and is self-graded 'strong'. ERBB2 (B) appears in the census as a general pan-cancer gene rather than a melanoma driver \u2014 its own report states 'Causal genetic support in melanoma is weak' and grades the axis 'weak', with only 3 SNPs and no melanoma-driver role. On mechanistic/causal support that the target is relevant to melanoma specifically, A is probably better.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: Cancer Gene Census somatic_mutation driver flag across four melanoma subtypes (score 1.0); 1172 melanoma evidence rows; self-graded 'strong'.", "B: ERBB2 census entry reflects a general 'cancer gene' role, not a melanoma driver; 764 rows; only 3 SNPs; report explicitly states melanoma causal genetic support is weak; self-graded 'weak'."], "missing_evidence": ["Melanoma-specific human genetics (GWAS trait associations) is absent for both targets.", "Perturbation/functional evidence (e.g. CRISPR dependency in melanoma cell lines) not reported for either.", "Pathway-causality data distinguishing driver vs. passenger status in melanoma for either target."]}, "right_tissue": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "Neither target has melanoma-relevant tissue evidence. MTOR (A) returns only 2 CellMarker human records, both in irrelevant contexts (beta cell/Blood, multipotent progenitor/Stomach), with no melanocyte, skin, or melanoma entry and no disease-tissue enrichment. ERBB2 (B) returns 25 CellMarker records but its cancer-cell expression is concentrated in Breast, Bladder and Blood, again with NO melanoma/melanocyte or skin cancer-cell record. B has a larger raw record count, but on this axis raw breadth in unrelated tissues (Breast/Bladder) does not confer melanoma tissue relevance \u2014 the decisive question (is the target present, active, and disease-relevant in melanoma tissue/cell type) is answered negatively for both. Both rely on absent disease-context evidence, so they are materially similar failures on right_tissue.", "decisive_evidence": ["MTOR CellMarker: 2 human records, neither melanocyte/skin/melanoma (Beta cell/Blood; Multipotent progenitor/Stomach)", "ERBB2 CellMarker: 25 human records, cancer-cell expression concentrated in Breast/Bladder/Blood, no melanoma/skin cancer-cell entry", "Both explicitly lack any melanoma-tissue enrichment or melanocyte-specific marker signal"], "missing_evidence": ["Single-cell or spatial transcriptomics of melanoma tumors showing MTOR or ERBB2 expression in malignant melanocytes vs stroma", "Disease-state (melanoma) tissue immunohistochemistry or protein-level localization for either target", "Malignant-vs-stromal or patient-context expression comparison in melanoma for either gene"]}, "right_safety": {"relation": "tie", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both targets carry substantial on-target safety liabilities driven by broad normal-tissue essentiality and large real-world adverse-event burdens, with no clear ordering. A (MTOR) is broadly essential/ubiquitous; its clinically validated inhibitor everolimus carries 16,850 OpenFDA AE reports with dominant liabilities of systemic immunosuppression and on-target toxicity (stomatitis, epilepsy). B (ERBB2) shows broad normal expression across blood, mesenchymal, brain and epithelial cells, and its antagonist trastuzumab carries an even larger 36,591 AE reports with a well-known cardiotoxicity class effect. Neither has a demonstrable therapeutic-window advantage in melanoma: MTOR's liability is systemic immunosuppression, ERBB2's is cardiotoxicity plus wide normal distribution. The raw AE count is higher for trastuzumab but this is confounded by drug exposure/usage volume, so it does not fairly establish a worse intrinsic safety margin. Both are materially similar serious-liability profiles.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: everolimus 16,850 OpenFDA AE reports; MTOR broadly essential (mTOR Inhibitor Immunosuppressant EPC), systemic immunosuppression and on-target toxicity as dominant liabilities", "B: trastuzumab 36,591 OpenFDA AE reports; known HER2-antagonist cardiotoxicity class; broad normal-cell expression (T cell, beta cell, mesenchymal stem cells multi-tissue, radial glia, epithelium)", "Both are ubiquitously/broadly expressed with meaningful on-target toxicity and no melanoma-specific therapeutic-window advantage"], "missing_evidence": ["Exposure-normalized adverse-event rates (AEs per patient-treated) to control for differing drug usage volumes", "Quantitative genetic constraint metrics (e.g. gnomAD pLI/LOEUF) and knockout/essentiality phenotypes for MTOR vs ERBB2", "Grade/severity distribution and dose-limiting-toxicity comparison rather than raw report counts", "Any melanoma-tissue-specific safety or on-target toxicity data for either target"]}, "right_patient": {"relation": "A_better", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Neither target has an active or approved melanoma program and neither defines a biomarker-selected melanoma patient population, so both are weak on this axis. However, A (MTOR) has more genuine melanoma-specific clinical precedent: 7 melanoma trials of mTOR inhibitors (everolimus/temsirolimus/nab-rapamycin), including Phase 2 studies that actually enrolled melanoma patients. Although all are COMPLETED or TERMINATED with no approval, they represent real melanoma-directed clinical testing and a tested (if negative) therapeutic hypothesis in the target population. B (ERBB2) has only 3 matching trials, and none is a melanoma-selective HER2 program \u2014 the single HER2-directed one (NCT04639219 T-DXd) is a pan-tumor HER2-mutation basket that merely lists melanoma among ~11 histologies, and the other two are not ERBB2-directed. Thus B has effectively no HER2-selected melanoma patient population, whereas A at least has melanoma-enrolling precedent. Confidence is low because A's edge rests on negative/discontinued trials rather than positive clinical benefit.", "decisive_evidence": ["A: 7 melanoma trials of mTOR inhibitors including Phase 2 (NCT00521001, NCT01014351, NCT00591734) that actually enrolled melanoma patients \u2014 real melanoma-directed clinical precedent, though all COMPLETED/TERMINATED", "B: only 3 trials; the sole HER2-directed one (NCT04639219 T-DXd) is a pan-tumor HER2-mutation basket listing melanoma among ~11 histologies, and NCT02308020/NCT02983045 are not ERBB2-directed \u2014 no HER2-selected melanoma population", "Neither target defines a melanoma biomarker-selected population or has an active/approved melanoma indication"], "missing_evidence": ["Any positive efficacy signal (response rate, PFS/OS) from the melanoma mTOR-inhibitor trials to confirm therapeutic benefit rather than just enrollment", "Prevalence of a HER2-mutant or HER2-amplified melanoma subpopulation that could define a targetable ERBB2 patient group", "Unmet-need and endpoint data specific to any biomarker-defined subset for either target"]}, "right_commercial": {"relation": "B_better", "confidence": "medium", "rationale": "On commercial attractiveness, B (ERBB2) is stronger. TheraSAbDab lists 20 anti-ERBB2 therapeutics including six approved agents (trastuzumab, pertuzumab, margetuximab, disitamab ADC, zanidatamab, zenocutuzumab) plus multiple Phase II/III assets \u2014 a mature, commercially validated franchise with a large ready-made asset base that could be repositioned. A (MTOR) has 0 antibody therapeutics and only completed/terminated Phase 1-2 melanoma combinations, with mTOR inhibitors monetized only in unrelated indications (renal/breast/TSC). Neither target has a melanoma indication, so melanoma-specific whitespace is genuinely unproven for both \u2014 that caveat cuts confidence and is why this is not high. But B's superior commercial maturity, competitive positioning, and repositionable approved-asset depth give it a clearer market opportunity than A, which has essentially no commercial melanoma vector and no antibody presence at all.", "decisive_evidence": ["B: TheraSAbDab count=20 anti-ERBB2 therapeutics, \u22656 Approved (trastuzumab/pertuzumab/margetuximab/disitamab/zanidatamab/zenocutuzumab) + Phase II/III assets", "A: TheraSAbDab count=0 for MTOR; all 7 melanoma trials completed/terminated, no active or approved melanoma indication", "Both franchises lack any melanoma indication, so melanoma-specific whitespace is unproven for A and B alike"], "missing_evidence": ["Direct evidence of competitive crowding or active pipeline density in melanoma specifically for either target", "Market-size or pricing data for a melanoma indication vs. incumbent standard-of-care", "Evidence of any biomarker-defined melanoma subpopulation (HER2+ or mTOR-pathway-activated) that would define a differentiated niche"]}, "tractability": {"relation": "B_better", "confidence": "low", "rationale": "Both targets are maximally tractable at the intrinsic level: each is Pharos Tclin (approved-drug target), Kinase family, with approved agents and extensive literature (MTOR 2295 pubs; ERBB2 3216 pubs). On the pure tractability axis they are near-identical, so this is close to a tie. The slight edge to B (ERBB2) is modality breadth and ligand richness: ERBB2 has a demonstrably drugged extracellular/kinase surface with BOTH multiple marketed small molecules AND a deep, curated antibody/ADC arsenal (TheraSAbDab count=20, including approved trastuzumab, pertuzumab, margetuximab, disitamab ADC, zanidatamab, zenocutuzumab). MTOR is drugged only via intracellular small-molecule inhibitors (mTOR-inhibitor class, e.g. everolimus) and returns 0 antibody therapeutics \u2014 narrower modality-target fit. More validated modality options and developable molecules across both small-molecule and biologic space gives ERBB2 marginally stronger tractability. Note: this is target-modality feasibility only; melanoma-specific indication weakness affects other axes, not tractability.", "decisive_evidence": ["Both Tclin, Kinase family (Pharos): MTOR P42345; ERBB2 P04626 \u2014 intrinsic tractability parity", "ERBB2 TheraSAbDab count=20 with multiple Approved antibodies/ADCs + marketed small molecules \u2192 two independent drugged modalities", "MTOR TheraSAbDab count=0 antibodies; drugged only via small-molecule mTOR inhibitors (everolimus/temsirolimus) \u2192 single modality axis"], "missing_evidence": ["Structural pocket / co-crystal and high-quality ligand (e.g. ChEMBL potency, DrugBank) comparison for each target", "Melanoma-specific delivery/assayability feasibility for either modality", "Developability metrics (selectivity, PK) distinguishing the two beyond approval status"]}}}};